28-year-old chef found dead in San Francisco mall
Only recently, a 28-year-old chef who moved to San Francisco was found dead in the stairwell of a local mall this week.
The victim's brother says he did not know of anyone who wanted to harm his brother. "He had finally got his affairs in order."
The body found at the Westfield mall Wednesday morning was identified as 28-year-old Frank Galicia of San Francisco, the San Francisco Forensic Science Agency said.
The San Francisco Police Department says the death is being investigated as a homicide.
The victim's brother, Louis Galicia, told broadcaster ABC's KGO radio station in San Francisco that Frank, who previously worked as a chef in Boston, had found his dream job when he became chef at San Francisco's Sons & Daughters restaurant six months ago.
A spokesman for Sons & Daughters restaurant said the death was a shock to them all.
"We are a small and tight-knit team, like a family. Our regret is great," the rep says.
"Our thoughts are with Frank's family and his friends."
Louis Galicia says Frank first lived in hostels, but he had finally got his affairs in order.
"He found an apartment, and he had a girlfriend," Louis Galicia told station KGO.
Louis Galicia says he knew of no one who wanted to harm his younger brother.
"He was kind and big-hearted.
Her way of being together with family was cooking for all of us," says Louis Galicia.
"He never wanted to get into an argument with anyone.
He was a brother who went with the flow.
Despite all the injustices going on in the world, she was an uncut diamond who shone every day," he says.
Anyone with information about the incident is asked to call the San Francisco Police Department tip line at 415-575-4444.
Strike-hit junior doctors call for new industrial action
Representatives of Britain's junior doctors (mostly those who specialise in Finland) have appealed to their trade union and asked for permission for further industrial action in a dispute over a new employment contract.
The Junior Medical Committee (JDC), part of the British Medical Association (BMA), is to ask its entire board for support for further industrial action from early September.
The JDC said ministers had not resolved the problems with the deal.
Junior doctors and medical students rejected the deal with the BMA in a vote in July.
58% of the members who took part in the vote rejected the agreement.
Ellen McCourt, chair of the Junior Medical Committee, posted a letter to JDC members on Twitter on Thursday night in which she says the government has "relentlessly kept quiet" about the issues that McCourt said led to the rejection of the deal.
The letter reads: "In light of this, the JDC Board, in its vote, has rejected a whole new proposal for a contract and demands that new formal negotiations be held on all our concerns.
In response to the Government's silence, the JDC Government has today submitted a formal request to the BMA Government seeking permission for incremental widening industrial action from early September."
The controversy has already seen junior doctors go on strike six times this year, which included the first complete work stoppages ever seen in the history of Britain's public health system.
Johann Malawina, head of junior doctors at the BMA, resigned after the vote, saying he did not accept negotiated contract terms that the BMA had recommended.
Speaking to BMA members during pre-vote meetings, Malawina said the deal was good and should be approved. The vote was attended by 54,000 junior doctors and medical students.
Following the vote, Health Secretary Jeremy Hunt said the agreement would come into force and apply to doctors in England.
Russia and Turkey: an alliance of outsiders?
It was a gesture that ended the crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met Tuesday to shake hands in reconciliation and bring to an official end an eight-month war of words and economic sanctions.
However, as Vladimir Putin took on his Turkish counterpart in the Golden Hall of his St Petersburg palace, I had the clear impression that the greater desire for reconciliation lay with Ankara.
The two sides shook hands,
but Putin's smile looked thin and little of him oozed warmth even by his own reserved standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, by contrast, repeatedly spoke of his "good friend" Mr Putin – five times, according to one report.
I couldn’t count myself.
He also promised that relations with Russia would be even better than before the crisis.
The next day, a newspaper in our country wrote that Erdogan had behaved as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I understood his enthusiasm just the opposite.
But the constant coolness emanating from Putin showed that the Russian head has forgotten nothing.
In fact, the first thing Putin mentioned in his opening speech was the cause of the crisis: Turkey shot down a Russian combat aircraft on the Syrian border.
Moscow's reaction at the time of the incident was furious.
Putin attacked Ankara with harsh words and accused him of stabbing him in the back.
The insult was all the greater because it came from a supposed friend.
It will be difficult, perhaps even impossible, to regain true trust.
Public opinion in Russia has also changed since November.
For months, state-controlled media waged a thorough and aggressive campaign against Ankara.
Suddenly, though, it seemed that the Turks were the cause of it all.
Among the most serious were accusations by top officials that Erdogan's own family has profited from illegal oil trade in ISIS-controlled areas of Syria.
Erdogan has emphatically denied the accusations.
But the official message from St Petersburg was that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting was only arranged so that Putin received the apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
In this way, Russia could gain some kind of victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of declaring a truce are clear.
Above all, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after he was nearly ousted from power last month in a failed coup.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have clearly shaken him as well.
There is also a financial motive for reconciliation.
Russian sanctions have hit Turkey hard, especially the charter flight ban, as normally several million Russian tourists travel to Turkish shores each year.
That number has plummeted by nearly 90%.
As for Russia, tour operators and charter companies will surely breathe a sigh of relief when air traffic can eventually resume.
They put their faith in a late-season rush to the Mediterranean.
And as recently as this week, state television has predicted that the price of fruit and vegetables will fall once Turkey's agricultural imports are allowed to resume.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," was the wording of an article in the financial magazine Vedemost.
But the visit also had greater political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what it sees as a lacklustre response to the coup attempt.
Not forgetting the old resentment over the snail-paced Turkish EU accession talks and Putin's interference. Putin's eager to capitalize on cool relations and erode Turkey's ties with the West.
The Russian leader undoubtedly won bonus points from Ankara when it voiced its support for elected authorities after the coup attempt.
This was self-evident to Moscow, which has its own inveterate preoccupation with the transition of power.
Thus, at their summit in a flamboyant seaside palace, Russia and Turkey could convey an image described by one analyst as an "alliance of outsiders": two countries that feel they have been abandoned and mistreated by the West are joining forces.
Despite public reconciliation, the two still have major differences.
The most significant is Syria, where Moscow has carved out an image of itself as a peace-builder but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides.
It says much that after nearly three hours of initial negotiations, each president told a press conference that they had not touched on the subject at all.
Turkey's president deliberately refused to answer a question about the two countries' differences, while Putin in turn highlighted them.
There is no clear consensus between the two countries on where they might seek consensus in Syria.
Given the possibility of a full-blown disaster caused by Nato member Turkey shooting down a Russian combat aircraft, it is undoubtedly better that, after months of open hostility, the two heads of state are even on speaking terms again.
Royal Bank of Scotland banks disappear from customers outside Scotland
The RBS chief executive said the bank's operations outside Scotland would be curtailed so that it would in future provide only business services, or back office services.
Royal Bank of Scotland is disappearing from customers outside Scotland.
Ross McEwan told broadcaster BBC Scotland that the RBS brand was originally linked to the bank's global ambitions.
The bank was forced to backtrack from its targets when it all but collapsed eight years ago and had to be bailed out.
In that time, brand strategists have used RBS to protect other consumer finance brands.
It sponsors international sport for millions of pounds, with examples including Six Nations rugby and Wimbledon champion Andy Murray.
But now it has been deemed right to let more national brands into the foreground.
Royal Bank of Scotland will remain available to Scottish customers but will not be abbreviated as RBS.
In England and Wales, all RBS names will be changed to NatWests, with the exception of head office and stock market listing.
The Ulster Bank brand is already in use in the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland.
There are also other smaller private banking brands that will be given greater weight, such as Coutts, Adam & Co, Drummond and Holt's Military Bank.
Mr McEwan was interviewed during a presentation to customers and staff in Inverness-shire.
He told BBC Scotland: "RBS will become an investment brand and the one that our staff are employed by because we are now becoming much more of a bank of different brands.
Because the bank itself became a global brand, RBS also became a global brand.
Now our aspirations are no longer global, but local.
Each of these brands represents something quite different in their own community, and our people work with customers under these brands."
RBS has already announced it is ending its sponsorship of Six Nations rugby, and it has raised the profile of various brands in sports sponsorship.
"Now is the right time for us to move into a bank with different brands because the bottom line is how are we going to be able to make the bank better for customers," says the bank's chief executive.
"It would have been very scathing three years ago if we had said we were going to be an excellent bank for our customers and introduced brands.
But the work we do and our focus on customer needs rather than our own has changed a lot.
We can bring those brands back again, so I think the time is right."
