Putin sacks administrative chief Sergei Ivanov
Russian President Vladimir Putin abruptly dismissed his chief of administration, Sergei Ivanov.
Ivanov has been part of Putin's confidant inner circle for several years.
Ivanov, 63, was now appointed special representative for environment and transport.
A statement issued by the Kremlin said President Putin "decided to relieve Ivanov of his duties as head of the Russian presidential administration," but the reasons for the dismissal were not disclosed.
Anton Vaino, who has been Ivanov's deputy chief since 2012, was appointed to the position.
Persecution, 44, is a former diplomat.
Born in Tallinn in 1972, Vaino graduated from the prestigious Moscow State Institute of International Relations (MGIMO) and has previously worked at the embassy in Tokyo.
Later, he headed the presidential protocol department and the Cabinet Office, according to the Kremlin's Russian-language Web site.
Persecution thanked Putin for his appointment in these words: "I am grateful for your trust.
I think the most important task of the administration is to support your actions as head of state, which means making draft laws and overseeing how the instructions you give are implemented."
Speaking to a Russian broadcaster on Friday, Putin said Ivanov had himself asked to resign and recommended Persecution as his successor.
Are the smiles real?
This move has caused confusion in Moscow.
Sergei Ivanov has long been close to Vladimir Putin, and like Putin, he has a KGB past.
As head of administration, he was one of the most powerful men in the country.
In a meeting with President Putin shown by Russian state television, each said Ivanov was withdrawing from the job at his own request.
Despite the smiles shown to the cameras, the explanations convince few, especially in the run-up to such a parliamentary election.
Are the firings the result of some kind of power struggle?
No one knows yet.
In Russia, the official claim that a man hailed as a possible president suddenly wants to lead Russia's environmental policies has been met with great suspicion.
The Kremlin website presents Ivanov's words to Putin, in which he says: "It is true that at the beginning of 2012 I asked you to give me responsibility for this highly complex and to some extent even inconvenient task for four years.
Now I've served as the president's chief of administration for four years and eight months.'
Ivanov assumed the post in December 2011.
Prior to that, he served as Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Defence.
He is a member of Russia's Security Council and, like Putin, a former member of the state security service, the KGB.
When Putin was head of the Federal Security Service (FSB), which replaced the KGB, in the late 1990s, Ivanov was appointed his deputy chief.
When Putin came to power, he named Ivanov as one of the five people he trusted most.
It was once thought that Ivanov might become Russia's president after Putin's second term, as the constitution would have prevented Putin from being elected to a third term.
But the task went to another one close to Putin, Dmitry Medvedev.
Putin became prime minister, then returned to the presidency just three and a half years later.
