Queensferry overpass now connected to Fife
The £1.35 billion project is now due to be completed by May 2017.
Engineers have connected the north deck and land bridge of the Queensferry overpass, meaning the bridge is now connected to Fife.
It is the first of four sections between the "deck fans," which are now almost complete around the bridge's three columns.
The bridge section from Fife is now 600 metres long and weighs 30,000 tonnes.
It contains 10,000 tons of steel and 20,000 tons of concrete and 46 slant wires.
The £1.35 billion project is now due to be completed by May 2017.
Keith Brown, the Cabinet Office minister responsible for the economy, visited the site today and was one of the first to be able to walk from the land to the bridge.
Mr Brown says: "This is a historic and symbolic moment in the construction of the Queensferry overpass.
We are all witnessing a really significant step forward in the construction of the bridge, and more than 30,000 pieces of concrete and steel have been used to build this section of the bridge alone.
Despite the massive size and weight, the construction of the bridge section between the land bridge and the bridge deck is a subtle operation that requires extremely precise installation tolerances.
Nearly 79% of the entire bridge deck is now in place, and the remainder of the deck is getting its concrete deck casting in Rosyth today, which means the deck is ready to be lifted into place."
Michael Martin, Forth Crossing Bridge Constructors project manager, says: "The completion of the first section of the bridge is always a major urinal in any bridge project.
In this fantastic project, this section represents the pinnacle of the road and civil engineering sector.
After the last section of the road deck was installed and connected to the road deck of the North Tower post, we then had to close the remaining northbound (i.e., landbound) gap.
This was done by pulling the northbound viaduct 700 millimetres southwards.
This was a massive and at the same time very precise operation.
Massive because the viaduct measures 222 metres in length and weighs about 6,000 tonnes and had to be pulled up at an inclination of about 3 per cent.
And high precision, because the tolerances that the team had to comply with were very small – only a few millimeters.
Fortunately, everything went well.”
