They were really lucky in their journey."
Pokémon Go hunt brings health and happiness
It's fascinating to watch the world change.
Over the past decade, many have lamented why teenagers and children no longer go out to play, preferring to stay inside and stare at their screens.
Pokémon Go gets people off the couch and on the move.
Originally, screen time was taken up only by watching TV, then, in addition, came video games and, most recently, smartphones.
So it's great to see that technology and exercise are not mutually exclusive.
Pokémon Go is a game app whose characters come from a video game created in the 1990s (which was later also made into a cartoon series, playing cards and other accessories).
Like many popular cultural phenomena, this one lobbed a little before the new game became available in the U.S., Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries was delayed due to huge interest that overwhelmed servers.
In just a few days, the number of users of Pokémon Go overtook Tinder and was nearly as high as Twitter.
So how does the game work?
Briefly explained, players go out in search of Pokémon on their smartphones, which are tracked using GPS. When a Pokémon is found, it can be "photographed" (using a screen shot of the phone) or "hijacked."
The craze has captivated a generation who played the video game when they were younger and lifted their butts off the couch.
In the US, the game has significantly increased the number of steps an "average person" takes in a day.
The Washington Post recently reported, from the Cardiogram app for the Apple Watch smartwatch, that found within two days of the game's launch that the number of people moving for 30 minutes a day rose abruptly from 45 percent to 53 percent. Cardiogram tracks 35,000 users.
The company does not know which of the users is playing Pokémon Go, it only sees the raw data of the exercise amounts.
Many public health campaigns encouraging people to get off the couch and exercise for at least 30 minutes a day have fallen on deaf ears because the campaigns have been boring and their advertising people have looked unhappy.
However, the importance of exercise should not be underestimated.
Those who exercise regularly are less likely to develop cancer or depression.
Exercise helps with weight control, lowers blood pressure, prevents diabetes and brings a large number of other benefits.
The great thing about Pokémon Go is that it gets people out to do something they enjoy.
In this way, it achieves three basic health benefits – exercise, fresh air and sun and joy.
It is even possible to make new friends during the hunt.
As usual, this phenomenon includes frowning frolics.
And yes, someone can walk into a door while playing.
What about it?
The breakthrough has been made.
For while smartphone apps like Fitbit might have already tracked your activity in the past, they didn't give you a reason to get going, as Pokémon Go does.
The allure of novelty will disappear, and usage will decline in time.
But thanks to the success of Pokémon, there will be more games that combine apps and virtual reality with activity in the real world, boosting the physical activity of people going on the hunt and improving their fitness and health.
