Police say three people who listened to music in car were victims of serial killer
Two women and one 12-year-old girl were killed in Phoenix's deadliest massacre in 10 years. The victims were sitting chatting in a car and listening to music when they were shot, according to a police release issued Thursday.
Authorities say that on June 12, Angela Rochelle Liner, Stefanie R. Ellis and Ellis' daughter, Maleah, were shot in a car parked on the side of the street.
The shooter was standing on the passenger side of the car, from where he fired eight shots with a handgun and then fled in another car, the statement says.
Police suspect the triple slaying may not have been caused by the robbery because the attacker did not take the purses or the $2,900 found in the possession of the other adult victim.
Phoenix police spokesman Sgt. Jonathan Howard says police are now investigating whether the killing is linked to four earlier attacks.
A total of seven people have been killed and two wounded in nine attacks, mostly in Hispanic-populated areas, in the past four months.
"What the events have in common is that they have occurred in residential areas in front of homes," Howard told television and radio broadcaster CBS affiliate KPHO earlier this month.
The suspect is believed to have several vehicles, including a brown Nissan from the late 1990s, a black BMW from the late 1990s and a white Cadillac or Lincoln.
Investigators do not want to reveal what led them to conclude that the attacks are linked and that their perpetrator is the same.
Ellis, 33, was taken to hospital for his injuries, where he later died.
Liner, 31, and Ellis' daughter Maleah died instantly at the scene.
