Mother of 6-year-old boy with microcephaly: 'Things are getting better'
Like most 6-year-olds, Edmund Picciuto likes singing, toys and, of course, his mother.
But unlike most other peers, Edmund has microcephaly, or congenital small-headedness, caused by a genetic disorder in his mother, Elizabeth Picciuto, that he was unaware of while pregnant.
"When I first brought Edmund home, my first thought was, "I'm not going to make it through this.
I'm not gonna make it.
I didn't commit to this.
Which is not true at all – of course you are committed to it," he says.
Elizabeth and her husband Vincent were told that Edmund might never recognise them and might not live at all.
Some of the doctors went as far as to suggest placing the child in institutional care.
"My first reaction was that I didn't think such a practice existed at all anymore," says Picciuto.
Edmund walks with the help of a walker.
Edmund sat up and didn't start crawling until he was 3, and he still doesn't speak.
But he's slowly going at his own pace.
He walks assisted and rides a bicycle.
He likes to play with his two brothers and loves to sing.
Elizabeth shows off a sign invented by Edmund, by which he means "sing for me."
"We're teaching him sign language," Picciuto told CBS News.
But that doesn't just mean regular sign language; it also includes signs invented by Edmund himself.
Microcephaly can be caused by a number of different diseases: hereditary, as in Edmund's case, or viral infections during pregnancy, such as measles or Zika virus.
The symptoms and prognosis vary greatly.
It is still too early to estimate how it will affect the lives of those affected by the Zika virus.
Picciuto recalls the emotional storm of an uncertain future.
“I kept saying, ‘What will happen to us?’
How are we going.”
And he still doesn't know.
"It's been a long time since I've asked for a prognosis. I don't think anyone is going to be able to give me one."
But Picciuto has some hope-giving advice for mothers whose children have birth defects caused by the Zika virus.
"Things are getting better.
Things tend to work out.
You love your child, and your child loves you.”
