A drug costing around £2.40 a day can reduce the risk of a heart attack
Thousands of heart attack patients are being given access to the drug, which costs around €2.40 a day, after officials recommended it be given to more people and for longer-term use.
The anti-clotting drug ticagrelor reduces the risk of further heart attacks in heart disease patients.
The drug is already being given 12 months after a heart attack, reducing the risk of a stroke or another heart attack.
The National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence (NICE), part of the UK's public health system (NHS) and assessing the introduction of new treatment methods, has instructed that ticagrelor should be given to patients for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems.
