About 140,000 people in England have a heart attack each year, with a quarter having a heart attack come back or having a stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by fatty material building up in the walls of blood vessels, which generates plaques.
If the plaque ruptures, it can create a blood clot that prevents blood from reaching the heart and causing a heart attack.
And if a blood clot breaks loose, it can travel with the blood supply and block blood flow to the brain, resulting in a stroke.
The risk of a new attack is higher in people who have had a heart attack once.
Ticagrelor, made by Britain's AstraZeneca and sold under the brand name Brilique, reduces that risk by reducing the likelihood of plugs.
Today's draft NICE guidance recommends that ticagrelor should be given for the next 90mg for 12 months, then reduced to 60mg, plus aspirin twice a day for a further three years.
Professor Carole Longson, of the Centre for the Evaluation of Treatment Adoption (NICE), says: "Although effective methods of treatment are available to effectively prevent disease progression and the onset of symptoms, up to a quarter of people who have had a heart attack have a new seizure or stroke – often with fatal consequences.
Fear of relapse can have a very negative impact on a person's quality of life.
We have received evidence that ticagrelor in combination with aspirin is effective in reducing the risk of further heart attacks and strokes in people who have already had a heart attack.
The recommendation to temporarily use ticagrelor increases treatment options for thousands of people who will benefit from it."
Due to the limited data on the efficacy and safety of ticagrelor, especially with regard to the risk of bleeding, if used for more than three years, the draft guidance does not recommend the use of the treatment method for a longer period.
