The Greenland shark (Somniosus microcephalus), also known as the ice shark, does not reach sexual maturity until the age of 150.
It could live for another 250 years after that, a new study reports.
The figures make the species the longest-lived vertebrate in the modern world.
In the animal kingdom, it is only overtaken by the Icelandic clam, with the oldest known specimen dated to the age of 507.
