Because the rate of growth is slow, only about one centimeter a year, according to trackers, adult individuals have been forcibly living for a long time.
But for how long?
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues found out.
He determined the ages of adult ice sharks from 28 females trapped in fishermen's gear.
The age of the fish was revealed by radiocarbon dating of eye lenses.
The average age of the sharks studied turned out to be at least 272 years.
The two largest fish in the sample, the 493- and 502-centimeter Amazonian fins, were revealed to be about 335 and 392 years old, respectively.
Because previous studies have found that ice shark females do not reach sexual maturity until they are more than four metres tall, the researchers calculated that they are about 150 years old at that point.
