Gunpowder gas is the first smell that has been practiced with Heila, says Suntio, the owner of Heila the dog.
Security situation and e-commerce main reasons
Heila is Customs’ first dog specialised in finding weapons and explosives and will be located at Helsinki Airport next year.
If necessary, the tasks may also take Heila and Suntio to other border crossings and ports.
However, the airport will be Heila’s main workplace, because the international security situation has changed due to the serious terrorist attacks in Europe.
The attacks in Paris and Brussels caused measures to be taken at Customs, and after the attacks, control has been strengthened, says Mikko Grönberg, the inspector general of Customs.
Another main reason for training a dog with weapons and explosives is the postal deliveries through Helsinki Airport.
As a result of increased internet trade, up to 40 million items of mail pass through the airport each year, including weapons supplies and explosives ordered from abroad.
In recent years, Customs has made some 300 discoveries related to weapons, weapons parts, ammunition and explosives, as well as their starting materials, among online shopping, passenger aircraft luggage and air cargo at Helsinki Airport.
Heila will work in different parts of Helsinki Airport.
It will be looking at checked baggage and mail items.
In the future, ports will benefit greatly by being able to go through large container areas and mark areas that require further investigation, says Grönberg.
Based on Heila’s performance, Customs will assess whether more weapons and explosives dogs will be trained in the future.
Mr Grönberg is hopeful about the idea.
School in Kirkkonummi
Heila-puppy’s training is coordinated by the Finnish Customs dog school in Kirkkonummi.
Suntio also attends training sessions with Heila’s police and Defence Forces experts.
The police have strong experience in training dogs and the Finnish Defence Forces has expertise in explosives.
Customs, together with other authorities, decides which odors Heila is taught to identify.
Heila is always trained as needed, says Grönberg.
Heila’s colleagues at Helsinki Airport include six drug dogs from Customs and the money and drug dog Massi.
Labrador Heila has been chosen from a litter of ten puppies.
The criteria for choosing a dog for the airport include briskness and hunting instinct, as well as calmness because the dog is dealing with weapons, explosives and streams of people.
Heila, who lives at Suntio’s home, is a close colleague of the customs inspector, but also a family member.
Nothing can be done without him at home, he laughs.
Subtle orders go straight to Heila.
The Ilta-Sanomat cameraman loses the camera mic cover for the fast dog, but Heila returns what appears to be a soft toy immediately on the "disconnect" command.
Tough competition for working dogs
Heila’s initial training will be completed next year.
There are still level tests ahead, next in October, to assess whether the training is sufficient for demanding jobs.
Heila can be seen working at Helsinki Airport next year, if everything goes according to plan.
Unfortunately, passengers cannot come and pet a dog wearing a work vest,” Suntio reminds.
The cost of one working dog is about 60000-70000 euros per year.
They have a working age of about seven to eight years, up to ten, after which they retire to the care of their owner.
The working days can be long, from eight to ten hours, but the active work periods only last from ten minutes to a couple of hours.
There is strong competition to become a working dog owner at Customs.
About 20-30 Customs employees applied to become Heila’s owner.
Luck fell on Suntio, who has never had a working dog before, but he has years of experience in dogs and control tasks at Customs.
