The news and outrage spread widely on Wednesday and was written about by online publications such as The Verge and Motherboard the day after Snapchat said it had removed the filter.
The company gave the following explanation: the lens was intended as a tribute to anime characters, not as a caricature of Asian people.
But for observers who have experienced racism, the lens was a reminder of offensive stereotypes.
Some vehemently denied the anime metaphor.
Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose tweet about the images was widely shared, said in an email that the lens was "offensive and awkward to say the least."
He adds: "It's hard to dispute the juxtaposition of highly tasteless Asian caricature with filter effects.
It shows that the filter is not just a "yellowface," but one taken to a degrading extreme."
Snapchat isn't the only company that needs to avoid these cultural traps.
American culture seems to be in a never-ending struggle for diversity and social inclusion, from corporate governments to Hollywood to the gadgets we carry with us.
Snapchat's large audience is made up of young people from more diverse ethnic backgrounds than their older counterparts. This could mean they are likely to expect discretion even more.
"When one of Snapchat's lenses creates an image that offends the user, these types of things don't go unnoticed very easily anymore, as they did in the past," said 25-year-old Katie Zhu in an interview Thursday.
Mr. Zhu, who works as a product manager and designer on the Medium publishing platform, decided on Thursday to delete his Snapchat account and encouraged others to do the same.
In her post on Medium and in a phone interview, she said she believed the conflicts surrounding ethnicity reflected a lack of appreciation for diversity in Snapchat's hiring practices.
Zhu criticized the company's mostly white and male-only leadership and concluded his post with the hashtag: #DeleteSnapchat.
"It's either the case that there are no people of color on their one-sided staff, allowing them to make these kinds of decisions, or they have people of color as employees as well, but their status is not such that they would dare to give their opinion directly and easily" says Zhu, who is Chinese-American.
Other observers agree with him, but Snapchat has largely failed to respond to the claim.
The firm does not release figures on the ethnic backgrounds of its staff, citing its status as a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the ethnic backgrounds of its staff, but its spokesperson said the company has recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented groups of people and promoting inclusion within the company.
For his part, Zhu says he keeps his Snapchat account closed, adding: "I wonder if they really need more users like us to be able to say this is not OK."
Congressional expert group says military officials misrepresented intelligence on ISIS
On Thursday, a group of congressional experts released a report saying officers in the U.S. armed forces, known as Central Command, altered intelligence reports to give a more optimistic picture of the war against ISIS in Iraq and Syria than events on the ground suggested.
The Republican chairmen of the House Armed Services Committee, a subcommittee responsible for intelligence and defense appropriations, set up a task force with an interim report detailing "general dissatisfaction" among military intelligence analysts. Analysts say senior military officials glossed over their assessments of American actions against ISIS.
Central Command, also known as Centcom, is the United States military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, responsible for military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence results approved by senior CENTCOM leaders generally provided a more positive picture of U.S. counterterrorism efforts than the facts on the ground indicated, and were invariably more positive than those in analyses by other units in the intelligence community," according to a press release on the report.
“What happened at Centcom is unacceptable – our soldiers suffer when high-level policymakers are presented with the wrong analyses,” said California Republican Rep. Ken Calvert.
"Centcom executive errors extend to top tier of organization".
The 10-page report details ongoing problems in 2014 and 2015 with Central Command's descriptions and analyses of American efforts to train Iraqi forces.
While the report contains no conclusive evidence that the reports commissioned by Obama administration officials were fabricated, it gives analysts an impression that Centcom executives had pressured them to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by ISIS.
"In the first half of 2015, many of Central Command's press releases, statements, and testimony to Congress were significantly more positive than the events actually were," it said.
"For example, a Centcom official publicly issued a statement saying a major military assault to retake Mosul could take place as early as April or May 2015."
Mosul, Iraq's second-largest city, remains under ISIS control.
"After months of research, this is very clear," says Representative Mike Pompeo, Republican of Kansas, in a statement.
"From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the highest-ranking intelligence leaders in the U.S. armed forces manipulated the intelligence results obtained to downplay the threat of ISIS in Iraq."
Republicans set up the task force after learning of suspicions raised by analysts that intelligence about ISIS had been manipulated.
The report, released Thursday, will be followed by more detailed results, as investigations continue.
In addition, the Defense Department's inspector general has launched an investigation into Centcom's intelligence.
On Thursday, Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee released their own results, in part consistent with the Republican task force's conclusions.
"Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly limited process for evaluating intelligence on ISIS and Iraqi security forces," said Adam B. Schiff, a senior Democratic member of the committee.
Schiff said this process "delayed the release of the intelligence results, "violated the morale of analysts" and "insufficiently noted dissenting views."
But Schiff and Democrats said there was no evidence that the White House was trying to pressure Centcom analysts to adjust their conclusions to "predetermined or political official line."
The news site Daily Beast reported the preliminary results of a congressional inquiry on Tuesday.
Last August, the New York Times reported on an investigation by the Pentagon's inspector general that was launched as a result of lawsuits filed by Centcom analysts.
Pentagon spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans said in a statement that the Defense Department would not comment on the congressional report as long as the inspector general's investigation was ongoing.
Still, he says, "Experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex information, and the intelligence community and Department of Defense welcome a wholesome dialogue on these key national security topics."
The investigation has other repercussions besides seeking to determine whether the U.S.-led bombings in Iraq and Syria have been successful (an assertion made by an increasing number of defense officials).
But the allegations last year put into question how much confidence President Obama can have in Central Command and in giving honest assessments of the military mission in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis areas.
The criticism of the intelligence on ISIS echoes disagreements that emerged more than a decade ago when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker published a study showing that President George W. Bush's government, despite the objections of many analysts, advocated only small forces in Iraq and spent little time considering what would result from the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the insurgency over intelligence about ISIS.
Officials said last year Hooker's task force concluded that despite public statements to the contrary, airstrikes on ISIS-controlled refineries had not significantly weakened the terror group's economy because it had built makeshift refineries and was thus able to sell oil on the black market.
But the outcome of the investigation was not relayed outside Central Command, The Times reported in September.
Centcom's commander at the time, Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III, came under criticism last year after many lawmakers judged the testimony given to the Senate to have been overly positive assessments of the war.
General Austin retired in April, and was replaced as commander of Central Command by General Joseph L. Votel.
