Amid Olympic buzz, trampoline brings zen
Regardless of the location and time, the Olympics will inevitably come across.
Rio de Janeiro's events, rivalries and struggles seem to follow with a fervent message constantly and everywhere.
As if the Olympic flame itself were a flaming baton, passing from archer to swimmer, from swimmer to gymnast and from gymnast to triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read the newspaper or listen to your neighbour's conversation in the queue at the cafe without avoiding hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky or the row between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there's a guy named Logan Dooley.
Dooley, a first-time Olympian, charms with her smile and might well be the name on everyone's lips, visible and heard in prime time viewing and listening, popular with sponsors and appearing in feel-good TV ads, if only she were a swimmer, gymnast or even a swordsman.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, will compete for Olympic gold on the trampoline.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate all competitions equally.
Farther from the centre, partly in the shade are lesser-known sports such as air pistol shooting, archery, badminton and taekwondo.
We will always have a breaststroke, and may the championship stay with us for a long time.
But if I'm allowed to write a modest piece about my own special favourite, I'd like to draw attention to the understated charm of the trampoline.
Although the trampoline has been an Olympic sport since the 2000 Sydney Games, its visibility for the past 16 years has been so low that many people I interviewed didn't even know it was an Olympic sport.
Ignorance can be region-specific.
Of course, athletes from the United States have participated in the Olympic trampoline, but the country has never made the medals and did not advance to the finals until 2012.
In the men's trampoline, the medals seem to go to the Chinese and Russians, and on the women's side, the medals have been hogged by the Canadians.
China's Dong Dong and Canada's Rosie MacLennan will defend the gold medals they won in London this year.
Trampoline, however, has the charm of an underdog. Partly because to an uncivilised ear it sounds more appropriate for circus school than for the Olympics.
(I admit that I am not an expert, just a fan.)
The sport has its comic potential, which cartoons have used in the characters" endlessly continuous bounce scenes. But it also has the same dignity as gymnastics and swimming, that is, the sports that connect in a trampoline essentially.
The word trampoline comes from the Spanish word el trampolín, which means "the springboard."
Ambitious champions jump on a huge trampoline that catapults them to a height of nearly 10 metres. Before landing on their feet, jumpers must perform a series of acrobatic maneuvers such as twists, folds and flips.
According to the official Olympic program, jumps are graded based on performance, severity and "flight time."
Thirty-two athletes from 17 different countries are competing in Rio for the trampoline gymnastics championship. Of them, 16 are men and 16 are women.
The most common direction of Olympic sports is straight ahead.
In pursuit of gold, medal hopes have to get further, faster, up and over, sometimes across the finish line, other times back and forth around the field.
Beyond the finish line or the starting wall, they also have another goal to aim for in televised reportage, namely a world or Olympic record.
This single-minded pursuit is sublime, admirable, even fanatical – and even enough to bring the viewer to tears.
But I also find this a bit exhausting just watching the games.
This is where the trampoline offers respite.
On the trampoline, the direction is upwards.
The goal is not to move forward.
The gymnast bounces up weightless like an astronaut, falls down and effortlessly flits back up.
Of course, there is also a competitive aspect to the sport, and it's not easy either, but it doesn't involve a frantic rush to the finish line or jumping far, just a dreamy and fluid combination of time and gravity.
It's as close to Zen as only an Olympic competition can get.
The women's qualifying matches and finals will take place on Friday afternoon and begin at 1 p.m. local time and the men's corresponding races on Saturday at the same time.
NBC will air the finals as part of its afternoon coverage, which begins at 2 p.m. local time on both days.
Amid the Olympic mania bring a moment of calm and loveliness that, amid the general buzz, might go unnoticed.
And if awareness can only be raised by offering male athletes who appeal to the eye and objectifying them – as the US male gymnasts recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal – then Logan Dooley is just waiting for his panting new legion of fans.
An entire generation protests in Ethiopia, a longtime ally of the United States
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Government forces have forcefully broken up protests demanding political change across Ethiopia.
Witnesses say several protesters have been shot dead in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia falling apart?
For the past decade, it has been one of Africa's most stable countries and a reliable ally of the West, whose economy has grown rapidly.
But over the past few months, the country has been shaken by anti-government protests that are spilling over into ever wider areas.
Last week alone, thousands of people stormed the streets demanding fundamental political change.
Human rights groups said the government's reaction was relentless.
Witnesses said police officers shot and killed several unarmed protesters.
Videos purportedly from the protests late last year or early this year show youths being beaten with sticks by security forces forced to stand with their hands against a wall.
The top U.N. human rights official is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"Keeping the country united has always been difficult, and moving forward all the more so," said Rashid Abdi, research director of the International Crisis Group at the Africa Horn project.
In terms of population, Ethiopia is the second largest country in Africa after Nigeria, whose stability has been promoted by Western countries.
The US military and intelligence services are closely supporting the Ethiopians in the fight against terrorist threats across the region, especially in Somalia. Few African countries, if any, are getting this much help from the West.
Ethiopia's economy has been growing at a rapid pace.
Its infrastructure has improved radically, with the capital Addis Ababa even having a new urban train.
The streets of cities are usually calm, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia is still a long way from being a model democracy: human rights organisations have consistently reported on the government's repressive policies, opposition in the country is very limited and dissent is quickly muted.
Many people have been driven out of the country, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the wilderness.
But that could be about to change.
"If the people are suppressed and have no choice but to demonstrate, it will erupt out," says Seyoum Teshome, who works as a university lecturer in central Ethiopia.
"The whole youth is protesting.
A whole generation protested."
There are many topics of discontent, from land use to the governing coalition's stranglehold on power.
After last year's widely criticised election, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat previously belonging to the opposition, and as a result now control the entire parliament.
Meanwhile, tensions are rising along the Eritrean border, where an escalating situation claimed hundreds of lives in a battle in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less defeated in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden People's Liberation Front, may seek to exploit the turmoil and rearm.
There are many reasons why the embittered mood that has been smouldering under the surface for years is erupting right now.
The first is patently innocent: smartphones.
Only for the past couple of years have Ethiopians been able to communicate on social media as more affordable smartphones became common and internet availability improved.
Even when the government repeatedly blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, especially during demonstrations, however, many access the internet through proxies that conceal their whereabouts.
Many Ethiopian youths reported that this is how they invited people to the protests.
Another reason is increased solidarity between Ethiopia's two largest populations, the Oromo and the Amhara.
The Oromo and the Amhara are not natural allies.
Amharas from Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands have long dominated the country's politics and business and have dispossessed Oromos, much of whom are Muslim and live in lowland areas.
But this, too, is changing.
"The collaboration is deepening and we are getting under the same umbrella," says Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromo leader.
The largest demonstrations have been in the Oromo and Amharic regions.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly ruled by the Tigre tribe, which represents only about six percent of the population and yet controls the military, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third cause behind the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, was prime minister of Ethiopia for 17 years until he died of an unnamed illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius who could see around the corner.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at spotting the first signs of discontent and using envoys to mediate between the opposing sides.
"The current government lacks this essential instinct," says Abdi, the conflict researcher.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, stepped into Meles's shoes from near obscurity.
Unlike Meles, who hailed from the Tigre region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he does not have the confidence of security forces managed by the Tigre tribe.
Many fear this will mean more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced similar riots was in 2005, when thousands protested against an election that analysts say was first botched and then stolen by the government.
In the post-election unrest, many protesters were killed, though there were fewer deaths than in previous months, and the unrest ceased relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopia's leaders for forward-thinking infrastructure planning, such as a new urban train, and significant advances in the fight against poverty.
But internal resentment against Ethiopia's government has clearly not stopped it from intensifying.
And resentment is taking a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in the Amhara city of Gondar attacked businesses owned by tigres, and anti-Tigre hate speech is becoming more common on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the U.S. and other Western allies in a fraught situation.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned aircraft monitoring neighboring Somalia, but the U.S. says the base has recently been closed.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it also does not want its ally in an already volatile region to collapse.
"This requires a tight balancing act," says Abdi.
Donald Trump says he was being sarcastic in claiming Obama was the founder of ISIS
Donald J. Trump on Friday tried to pull back his words in the latest controversy to hit his campaign by insisting that he was not serious about claiming several times this week that President Obama and Hillary Clinton were the "founders" of the terrorist group ISIS.
The clarification raised new questions about the ability of the Republican half of the presidential candidate to communicate clearly to the citizens of his country.
Also getting into an awkward situation are his backers, who have to try to excuse their candidate in these tumultuous moments and explain comments he may not have intended.
Trump made the claim at an election rally Wednesday night and reiterated in various interviews Thursday that he really meant what he said when he claimed the president and Hillary Clinton created ISIS.
But early Friday morning, Trump tweeted and said his claim amounted to sarcasm.
In a tweet, Trump completely reversed his speech from the day before, when he said in several interviews that he was serious about his accusations.
When radio host and conservative Hugh Hewitt tried to help Trump soften his claim by stating that Obama is trying to destroy ISIS, the Republican presidential candidate refused to back down from his claim.
The most recent storm of criticism mounted as Trump tried to focus his campaign back on the economy as approval ratings fell.
Trump and Clinton delivered their economic policy briefings in Michigan this week.
On Friday, Trump tried to revisit the topic.
He warned on Twitter that Clinton's proposals would raise taxes, and found Clinton's speech boring.
Trump has defended himself with sarcasm before.
At the end of July, he faced widespread criticism when he appeared to urge the Russians to hack Hillary Clinton's email. He later explained his comments by saying: "Of course I was being sarcastic."
In this way, Trump is pushing the boundaries of political speech and pulling his words back when necessary.
"I believe it's his way of testing certain messages that elicit a response from his supporters. He watches how supporters respond to the messages, and then "clarifies" one way or another depending on the reactions," says communications expert Ruth Sherman, who has observed the language used by both presidential candidates.
"But I also think he understands his claims and knows they're all-round enough to pass through different sieves."
Instead of softening his statements to the election audience, Trump has in recent days changed his style to even more pungent as his approval ratings have continued to decline.
A new poll released Friday by NBC, the Wall Street Journal and Marist reported that Trump's support is significantly lower than Clinton's in North Carolina, Virginia and Colorado, while the situation in Florida is firmly even.
While Trump usually tries to avoid apologizing for his provocative speeches, he often accuses his critics of misinterpreting his words or failing to understand his sense of humor.
But after coming under increasing scrutiny in the final months of his presidential campaign, Trump's jokes have put his loyal supporters in the awkward position of having to publicly defend Trump's comments, however provocative they may be.
One of Mr. Trump's most prominent supporters, Rudolph W. Giuliani, the former mayor of New York City, vigorously defended the presidential candidate in an interview with CNN on Thursday.
"I consider what he said to be justified, political speech," replied Giuliani when asked if Trump was truthful in claiming Obama and Hillary Clinton founded ISIS.
"That's true in the sense that before Obama, Isis was almost unknown, a small organization that Obama completely mistakenly called a "lower league team" and that's why this happened, because he pulled the troops out of Iraq."
Most mainstream Republicans are trying to argue that the Obama administration, with Hillary Clinton as secretary of state, allowed ISIS to continue its efforts when it failed to deal decisively with the situation in the Middle East.
Ahead of Friday's election rallies in Pennsylvania, Trump continued to attack the media on Twitter, where he accused them of dwelling on his speeches and taking a discriminatory stance against him.
He mocked the "unworthy and pathetic" television commentators who are trying to find out about him, but he says they cannot succeed in doing so.
Some Democrats mocked Trump's explanation, saying it only shows more clearly that he is not fit to be president.
Cafe, which closed due to excessive rent rises, opens in Greenpoint
Verb Cafe was a bit of a busted coffee shop in Williamsburg, where cash was the only means of payment and there was no Wi-Fi, but which provided good coffee for 15 years.
Naturally, the cafe had to be priced out of its curbside spot on Bedford Avenue when the rent became exorbitant.
Soap Cherie, which replaced Verb Cafe in the summer of 2014, sells soaps shaped like cupcakes.
Locals find this loss of a cafe that has been dodged under middle-classisation deplorable.
Artist Molly Crabapple wrote on Twitter: "New York is changing, I know yes, but I still can't believe the CBGB club is no more, the Chelsea Hotel has been destroyed and the Verb is now a soap shop."
But while New York isn't what it used to be, it's also where new things are created.
Last November, Verb Cafe opened a new cafe in Greenpoint, just over a mile north of its original location.
The new Verb cafe has Wi-Fi and you can pay by credit card, but some of the employees are the same and the atmosphere is still unsophisticated.
The coffee is still good too.
The owner and manager of the new Verb cafe is Cisco Rodriguez, a longtime employee of the old cafe.
He started at Verb in 2001 and worked there until the end.
When a customer offered to fund the opening of a new cafe, he said he was very interested in doing it.
Rodriguez, 36, kept many things the same.
Verb orders bagels from the same supplier as before and uses the same espresso machine model.
In addition, it even reintroduced the lamps of the old Verb.
But Rodriguez says he also wanted to try something new and
Added new products to the list.
Bacon-and-egg-and-cheese sandwichies and capers and browned onion rings are available for the topping.
There are also dark rice bowls on the list.
You can no longer get beer from the cafe, but juices made from fresh fruit instead.
After running a coffee shop for nine months, Rodriguez says he noticed old regulars started going to Verb on a steady stream.
"Also, a lot of our old customers got priced out of Williamsburg," he says.
One such is Rebecca Oliveira, who went to the cafe recently on Sunday.
Oliveira, 34, previously lived in Williamsburg and regularly attended Verb.
Even after moving to Greenpoint, he took walks to Verb, then still in Williamsburg.
When Verb closed, he says he stopped drinking coffee for a while.
"I realised I liked Verb's coffee and culture," he says.
Now he's drinking coffee again, although on the Sunday in question he took a chai tea blend instead of his usual iced coffee, which is also a list novelty.
Another longtime customer, Tom Rosenthal, faithfully visited Verb since 2003.
He always went to the cafe before work and invariably ordered the same.
"I walked into the cafe every day at a quarter past seven, like a machine, and there they were already making my butter bagel with all the toppings," he tells me.
Photo: Rodriguez also wanted to try something new and brought new products to the menu.
Today, Rosenthal still orders his standard produce, but occasionally he varies the bacon, egg and cheese toppings on his bagel.
Rodriguez says he bears no grudges that the soap shop took the old place.
The owners of Soap Cherie even offered to make a special soap, which the Verb's own cold brewed coffee is used to make.
"We may yet take up the offer," Rodriguez says.
Poles who have traditionally lived in Greenpoint have also welcomed the cafe.
One of the new customers translated the menu into Polish, and Rodriguez says she is now looking for a suitable place for it so her new neighbors feel welcome.
The new location has brought other benefits.
A local juice company wants to bottle and sell the cafe's cold brew coffee.
The cafe may also expand to the adjacent building.
But for many customers, it's enough to give them their own old favourites from the new Verb.
Joseph Whitt was a regular in Williamsburg, and he says he was heartbroken when the cafe closed.
When a new place opened and I ordered a coffee there, it felt like arriving home," says Whitt.
"I missed the smell of the cafe."
The dreary food of the Great Depression in a new work: A Square Meal
In March 1933, shortly after becoming president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down for lunch in his Oval Office at the White House.
Known as a cultist, President Roosevelt had a penchant for the extravagant dishes of Fifth Avenue restaurants like foie gras pasty and Maryland tortoise soup.
That day, his menu was more modest: deviled eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and, for dessert, plum pudding.
"It was a show of culinary solidarity with people who are suffering," says Jane Ziegelman.
Her husband, Andrew Coe, adds: "It was also a message to the American people about how they should eat."
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, both work as food historians.
Coe's latest book, called Chop Suey, is about Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelman's latest book, called 97 Orchard, tells the story of an apartment building in a Lower East Side district through food.
Their new joint work is A Square Meal, published by Harper and published on Tuesday, which depicts the history of American food during the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The couple showed their own culinary solidarity when they agreed to meet with a reporter at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a small and regular lunch bar near the Flatiron skyscraper that opened the same year as the Great Stock Market Crash occurred, 1929.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese and olive-filled sandwich and 57-year-old Coe, meanwhile, ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and mixed vegetables.
When a reporter ordered meatloaf, the couple said it was a good fit for a discussion about eating during the Great Depression.
"The morsels were very popular," says Jane Ziegelman.
"People ate peanut loaf, liver loaf and bean loaf.
They were made from materials that were cheap and plentiful.
Imagine eating enough peanuts to last you a whole meal.”
Andrew Coe scowls.
"It must have weighed like lead in the stomach," he says.
Before the Great Depression, the American dining table, particularly in rural areas, operated on the buffet principle of "eat as much as you like."
Women made food for farmworkers, and freshly baked pies were served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
It was the Americans who had sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. A Square Meal is a chronicle of the ways in which the nation coped when abundance suddenly had to be abandoned.
"This was a time when food became a central and distressing talking point for Americans" says Coe and explains why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
Equally distressing was the new low-cost diet: according to Ziegelman, enigmatic dishes like morsels and casseroles became the main food, and casseroles were said to be "a great way to make the most of leftovers" because chefs could cover the not so appealing ingredients with cream sauce.
Fresh fruit was replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, which for years had been the centerpiece of the American meal, became a luxury used sparingly.
We tried strange blends where what mattered was the fulfilment of calorie and nutritional values rather than taste or even healthy kitchen sense.
While doing research for the book, which also includes recipes, Jane Ziegelman prepared peanut butter-filled oven onions used as a shortage dish.
"It didn't gain popularity at the dinner table," says Coe, to which
Ziegelman adds: "It was unreal.
Peanut butter and oven onions don't mix at all.
This was characteristic of many household recipes."
Household experts, such as Louise Stanley, who served as director of the Federal Household Agency from 1923 to 1943, guided the eating habits of citizens in an unprecedented and unique way.
They published recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines and encouraged women to be accurate budget-keepers and to rise to the challenge of making tasty dishes out of pancakes like carrot cream paghetti.
The A Square Meal book is a celebration of historic tidbits.
Particularly palatable are accounts of state leadership's reactions to its hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's "let me eat cake" attitude.
While he publicly extolled the simple food of his childhood on an Iowa farm, he himself ate, like the millionaire and sophisticated gentleman he had become.
"He liked continental European cuisine, like fish and cucumber sauce" says Coe.
"He almost ate in the gold-plated dining room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was completely alienated from reality."
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake had his wife, Eleanor, not encouraged him to set an example on his stomach.
As the book recounts, when Mrs. Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who had no interest in taste at all, the foods served at the White House were not only the dullest in Washington, but the worst prepared."
