Chili-powder-filled firecracker condoms to support elephant conservation in Tanzania
Conservationists in Tanzania have found an unusual way to keep elephants away from human settlements by throwing chili-powder-filled condoms at them.
The method has proved effective, and the Honeyguide Foundation, which came up with the idea a few years ago, along with the U.S.-based Nature Conservancy, has started a campaign to teach volunteers in villages in northern Tanzania how residents can protect their homes and plantations without harming elephants.
Not so long ago, spears were used to harass elephants.
Friday is World Elephant Day, which is dedicated to animal conservation.
"Having developed the method, we have seen a change in attitudes in these villages, as now villagers can have confidence that they will be able to keep elephants out of their fields without harming them," Damian Bell, executive director of the Honeyguide Foundation, says in a statement.
First, the intruding elephant is harangued by pointing a flashlight and sounding a horn.
If this doesn't work, throw in a so-called chilli cloud.
The ground chilli powder is placed in the condom together with the firecracker, and then the end of the condom is twisted shut so that only the fuse remains outside.
When the fuse is lit, the condom explodes open and spreads a fine cloud of chili powder into the air.
Usually, one cloud of spice is enough to drive an elephant away.
A last resort is a tosser that fires a firework known as a Roman candle into the air and generates a loud and bright explosion.
