However, it remains to be seen whether any charges will be brought against the motorists involved in the accident.
"Was it impossible to avoid the collision?
That will be left for the prosecution to sort out," says Hofstetter.
In the past five years, there have been two similar incidents that do not hold motorists accountable.
The newspaper said in each case, a person was walking in the dark on the freeway and the court ruled that motorists could not expect to bump into a pedestrian on the freeway in the middle of the night.
Last year, a police official was cleared of a charge of manslaughter against him after a collision with a man lying on the A1 motorway near Paynerne on one August night in 2014.
The tribunal heard that the 22-year-old victim had consumed high levels of alcohol and passed out on the road.
The tribunal ruled that the manner in which the police – who were responding to a distress call – were driving was justified and the man lying on the road was a "totally exceptional and unforeseen situation."
Anyone with information about the accident near Morges on Thursday is asked to call police on 021 644 83 46 or 021 644 44 44.
NASA climate model: Venus has been livable
According to NASA's new climate model estimates, Venus may have been habitable.
NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies (GISS) developed a model to study Venus' past using the same tools and algorithms used by climate scientists.
The model was intended to determine whether conditions on Venus might once have been similar to those on Earth, even though Venus is hot and waterless on the surface and its atmosphere is made up almost entirely of carbon dioxide.
According to previous presentations by scientists, Venus's slow spin rate can be explained by its thick atmosphere.
However, based on the latest simulation, it can be assumed that Venus has had a thin, Earth-equivalent atmosphere, and it has nevertheless been spinning slowly.
The model was also used to determine the topography of early Venus.
The planet likely had more arid areas than Earth, but may have had enough water and geographic variation to sustain life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
"In GISS's modeling, Venus rotates slowly and has a daytime face toward the sun of nearly two months at a time," said GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a press release.
This warms the surface and creates rain, which creates a thick cloud layer. The cloud layer acts like an umbrella and protects the surface from much of the sun's heat.
As a result, average climate temperatures are even a few degrees lower than Earth's current temperatures.
The model was used to create the story of Venus, which matches previous assumptions by planetary scientists about its trajectory.
However, while Venus may have been habitable, for several billion years it has been exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet light.
Its oceans evaporated, and ultraviolet light scorched the vaporized water.
As hydrogen escaped into space, all that was left was a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide and a deadly greenhouse effect – that is, Venus as it is today.
The researchers reported the results of the new Venus climate modeling in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy to step down as Avalanche coach
Patrick Roy resigned Thursday from his positions as coach of the Colorado Avalanche and vice president of hockey operations for the club, citing a lack of influence in team decision-making.
Colorado Executive Vice President/General Manager Joe Sakic confirmed the news and announced that the club will immediately begin seeking a new coach.
"For the past three years, I have fulfilled my duties as head coach of the Colorado Avalanche team and vice president of hockey operations for the club with energy, passion and determination," says 50-year-old Roy in a statement.
"Over the summer I have thought long and hard about how I could improve the squad, give it the necessary depth and take it to a higher level.
For this to be achieved, the coach and the club's vice president of hockey operations must be in full alignment with the organization.
He must also have a say in decisions that affect the team's performance.
These conditions are currently not met."
Sakic, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his investment in the team.
"Patrick told me about his decision today," Sakic says.
"We are grateful for everything he has done for our organization, and we wish him all the best for the future."
Roy was awarded the Jack Adams Award as the league's best coach of the year for his first season as head coach of the Avalanche from 2013 to 2014.
Under his leadership, the club got to 112 points and won the Central Division, but Colorado lost to Minnesota in the playoffs and hasn't made the postseason the past two years.
The Avalanche gained 39-39-4 points in the 2015-2016 season and were held to five points by the Minnesota Wild for the second Wild Card spot in the Western Conference.
Roy, a Hall of Fame goaltender, won four Stanley Cups in his career – two with the Montreal Canadiens and two with the Avalanche.
North Sea oil workers begin talks and suspend strike
Chief negotiators say wage strikes by North Sea oil workers will be interrupted as all sides in the dispute take part in a new round of talks.
Strikes have been held against Wood Group, an oilfield services company, on drilling platforms in the North Sea under the control of Royal Dutch Shell.
A joint statement from the two sides said: "Wood Group and the trade unions Unite and RMT confirm that they have agreed to resume the process in order to resolve the dispute."
From early next week, we will be holding a number of all-day meetings over the next few weeks to address the problems from fresh considerations.
Unions justified their recent action, which they said was the first in more than 25 years, in protest at possible pay cuts of up to 30 per cent.
Faced with negative market pressures, Wood Group will cut tariffs on its North Sea-based contractors by about 9 per cent this year.
The company's tariff reduction follows a 10 per cent cut in prices for onshore contractors in 20114.
The company said the additional cuts will give it the room to maneuver necessary to weather the market downturn.
Shell, meanwhile, has trimmed thousands of employees from its payroll and announced plans to leave oil and gas operations in as many as 10 countries. In doing so, it is looking to boost its operations following its mega-merger with British energy company BG Group.
Lower crude prices and economic conditions following the UK's decision in June to leave the European Union are putting pressure on energy companies.
Scottish MEP Dave Anderson met with Labour leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest labour conflicts experienced in an entire generation in the North Sea.
He said the North Sea was vital to the region's economy.
"In the North Sea and across the country, we need an economy that benefits the many and not just the few," says Anderson.
Less than $1.4 billion is expected to be spent on new projects in the North Sea in 2016, down from about $7 billion over the past five years.
Kepler measures star rotation rate in Pleiades cluster
The Kepler space telescope's latest mission has been to measure the rotational speed of stars, helping astronomers compile the most comprehensive list to date of the rotational speeds of stars in the Pleiades cluster.
Based on the new data, astronomers will be able to determine why stars in the same cluster rotate at different speeds and how the orbital periods relate to the planetary formation.
"We hope that by comparing the results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between a star's weight and age, and even the history of its solar system," Luisa Rebull, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the Pasadena-based University of Caltech, said in a press release.
The Pleiadian cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born about 125 million years ago, which means they are just reaching their adult age.
They are spinning faster than ever at the moment.
At the peak of the rotational speed, large amounts of stellar wind erupt from the growing stars.
These winds have a discouraging effect on the stars as they progress through the stars' magnetic fields.
As a star ages, its rate of rotation begins to slow.
Kepler measures the rate of rotation of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots (which correspond to sunspots).
The latest catalogued rotational speed data suggests that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller ones.
Rebull likens the stars to dancers – the larger ones spin more slowly than the smaller ones.
"We see from the "dance" of the Pleiades that slow-spinners are typically larger, while the fastest-spinners are typically very light stars," says Rebull.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory to compare the properties of stars relative to rotation rates.
"The Pleiades cluster provides a mainstay for theoretical models of the rotation of both younger and older stars," says Rebull.
We want to learn more about how, when and why stars slow down and stop dancing.
Rebull and his colleagues present their latest analysis of Pleiadian spin rates in three of their new papers, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
